Duration of must in spoken American English

Susanne Flach

2025-01-31

Background

This project was an interesting excursion into the analysis of spoken data, that came about almost by accident: do the two meanings of English must differ in their duration and other phonetic properties? Duration of this kind had not been studied at all, probably due to lack of data, but differences wouldn’t be surprising, as research has shown that homophones like time and thyme differ in duration (usually it’s the more frequent and/or more ‘basic’ meaning that is shorter).1

For this kind of analysis, we need a fairly large corpus, which comes with the trade-off that the word duration determination is coarse-grained and the audio quality is low (by traditional standards in phonetics). But the NewsScape corpus is a pretty interesting resource for many corpus-linguistics tasks. (See the RedHenLab for more info.)

The two meanings of must

English must has two meanings: the deontic meaning refers to what has to be done (We must be vigilant) while the epistemic meaning refers to a situation that is probably the case (He must be home; his car is in the driveway).2

The two meanings occur in very distinct lexico-grammatical environments. For example, if followed by a perfect (That must have been difficult), the meaning is nearly always epistemic, whereas if followed by a main verb (We must clean up this mess), the meaning is usually deontic. So the linguistic environment is a very reliable cue to the meaning of must, and because of the greater likelihood of co-occurrence, will also contribute to acoustic shorting.

The question(s)

In this project, I was interested in whether the two meanings also differ in duration, which has theoretical implications for word storage, but potentially also for lexical change in grammar. In general, durational differences are due to

  • Frequency of use in general
  • Frequency of co-occurrence with surrounding words (e.g., transitional probabilities)
  • Emphasis: putting emphasis on words will likely lead to longer duration
  • Speech rate: if the conversation is fast-paced, words will be shorter

The frequency-related properties are related to expectation: words that co-occur often, will be more easily retrieved from memory. Conversely, if a word is more unexpected, more effort will probably go into its articulation. In cases such as time or thyme and but and butt there is a noticeable frequency difference by orders of magnitude. No such difference exists between the two meanings of must, which are equally frequent. Differences in frequency are due to corpus composition – deontic must is more frequent in formal speech situations, while epistemic must is rather characteristic of informal and/or spoken-like discourse. In any case, their frequency differences are usually on the same order of magnitude.

As there was little research to go by in terms of hypotheses, I was mainly interested in exploratory analysis: do the two meanings differ in duration? If so, by how much? Are there more general differences between the two meanings?

The data

The NewsScape2016 corpus houses corpus-linguistically (NLP) processed data from US Network television. The closed-captions were force-aligned with the audio to produce annotations of beginnings of ends of words, from which the words’ duration in centiseconds could be determined.

The data can be extracted via a cql-based query common in corpus linguistics. The data points used in the analysis were semi-manually picked from a list of 20,000 uses of must. I then manually checked about 2,000 examples against the original video using RapidAnnotator, in order to remove unusable data (erroneous force-alignment, transcription, music, etc.) and to annotate meaning and emphasis. See Appendix.

The first columns include the match (must) and one word to its left and right. Meaning indicates whether it’s epistemic or deontic. Emphasis is a binary variable that indicates if the must use occured in a context of particular stress or emphasis. CS is the duration of must in 1/100th of a second (centiseconds). S

The binary categorical variables Meaning (deontic, epistemic) and Emphasis (yes, no) were hand-annotated while the datapoints were checked against the actual videos. Emphasis expresses whether the use of must occurs in an expression that is particularly emphasized (which will naturally effect its duration).

The numerical variables include the (main) outcome, duration, in CS (centiseconds, non-transformed)

Manually annotated: Meaning: deontic or epistemic Gender: male or female (annotator’s judgement) CS: duration of must in centiseconds (1/100th of a second) Duration: log-transformed CS SR: speech rate (in syllables/seconds), based on 200

Exploratory data analysis

Descriptive statistics

Overall, deontic must is substantially shorter than epistemic must, by raw numbers that is a difference of almost 50ms; epistemic must is also a bit less variable. This is a statistically

must |> 
  group_by(Meaning) |> 
  summarise(mean = mean(CS), sd = sd(CS))

Multifactorial: correlations

Of course the duration of a word depends on a variety of factors. First, if a word occurs in a context of rapid speed in general, then must will also be spoken faster. We measured “speech rate” as number of syllables per second in the context 200 words to the left and right of the occurrence:

ggplot(must,
       aes(SR, CS * 1000)) +
  geom_jitter(size = 2, alpha = 0.8, color = PB) +
  geom_smooth(se = FALSE, color = PG) +
  labs(title = "Duration by speech rate and emphasis",
       subtitle = "Faster speech leads to shorter *must* duration",
       x = "Speech rate (syllables/seconds)",
       y = "Duratiaon (ms)") +
  scale_color_manual(values = c(PB, PG))

ggplot(must, aes(Meaning, CS * 1000, fill = Emphasis)) +
  geom_violinhalf(
    data = must |> filter(Emphasis == "yes"),
    color = NA
    ) +
  geom_violinhalf(
    data = must |> filter(Emphasis == "no"),
    color = NA,
    flip = TRUE) +
  labs(
    title = "Duration by meaning and emphasis",
    subtitle = "Emphasis leads to longer duration",
    y = "Duration (ms)", x = NULL
    ) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c(PB, PG))

ggplot(must,
       aes(SR, CS * 1000, group = Emphasis, color = Emphasis)) +
  geom_jitter(size = 2, alpha = 0.8) +
  geom_smooth(se = FALSE) +
  labs(title = "Duration by speech rate and emphasis",
       subtitle = "Faster speech leads to shorter *must* duration",
       x = "Speech rate (syllables/seconds)",
       y = "Duratiaon (ms)") +
  scale_color_manual(values = c(PB, PG))

Appendix

I extracted the data from the NewsScape 2016 corpus, a collection of video transcripts from US Network television from the year 2016, which totals about 250 million words of running text. The programs are mostly from the ABC, CNN, or Fox. Closed-captions, which are obligatory in the US, are force-aligned with the video, and word duration is automatically extracted; if you are familiar with NLP or corpus linguistics, then think about word duration as a token-level annotation that is available in NewsScape2016, alongside traditional annotation layers like part-of-speech or lemma. The word duration annotation specifies where in the audio-video the word begins and where it ends, and we took, trivially, the difference between the two. (See the RedHenLab for more info.)

Cleaning & sampling

I extracted 20,000 uses of must, and semi-automatically removed all instances that are likely “unusable data” (e.g., misaligned text/audio, missing time stamps, etc.), or for which important metrics would not be available (more on this later). From the remaining data I randomly selected 2,000 examples, which I manually checked against the actual video snippets, and removed dirty data that:

  • Pauses of more than 500ms before and after must
  • Where no speech rate could be determined, i.e., no 200 usable tokens left and right

    • While Meaning was rather straight-forward, Emphasis was trickier: emphasis is clearly a non-binary property, especially as a property that affects word duration. The choice for a

    Emphasis was coded by myself and a collaborator, who was unaware of the goal of the project until after annotation; the data contains his annotations only.
